{I'll explain the details of the solid 4.g3 c5 5.Nf3 b6. It usually takes the
game towards a popular variation of the English opening where Black’s
dark-squared bishop is on e7 instead of b4. With a simple play, White usually
gets a comfortable plus.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 c5 5. Nf3 b6 6.
Bg2 Bb7 7. O-O {Black faces an interesting choice as he has the opportunity to
decide the future of the pawn formation. [#]} cxd4 (7... Bxc3 $5 8. bxc3 Nc6 $5
{This interesting move has been played by a number of strong players.} (8... d6
9. d5 e5 10. Nh4 O-O 11. e4 Bc8 12. f4 exf4 13. Bxf4 Ne8 {1/2-1/2 (39)
Makarichev,S (2505)-Dizdarevic,E (2415) Sarajevo 1982} 14. e5 $16) (8... Be4 {
This move has special relevance as it was the choice of the great David
Bronstein.} 9. Bf4 Nc6 10. dxc5 bxc5 11. Qd6 Rc8 12. Qxc5 Na5 13. Qxa7 Nxc4 {
½-½ (75) Romanishin,O (2595)-Bronstein,D (2560) Tallinn 1977} 14. Ne5 O-O $1
(14... Bxg2 15. Nxc4 Rxc4 16. Kxg2 O-O 17. Rfb1 $16) (14... Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Bxg2
16. Kxg2 $16) 15. Bxe4 Nxe4 16. Nxd7 Re8 17. Qd4 $16) 9. dxc5 $1 (9. Ne5 {
is a worthy alternative for White.} Na5 10. Bxb7 Nxb7 11. Bg5 Qc7 12. Qd3 (12.
Bxf6 gxf6 13. Ng4 f5 14. Nf6+ Ke7 15. Nh5 Rhg8 16. Qd2 Nd6 17. Qf4 Raf8 18. f3
f6 19. e4 $13 {1-0 (42) Ipatov,A (2587)-Nikolic,P (2619) Wijk aan Zee 2013})
12... Ng8 {1/2-1/2 (62) Ivanisevic,I (2614)-Jobava,B (2696) Novi Sad 2009} 13.
Nf3 h6 14. Bd2 Ne7 15. e4 O-O) 9... bxc5 10. Be3 d6 11. Bf4 Ke7 (11... e5 12.
Bg5 $16) (11... Na5 12. Qxd6 Qxd6 13. Bxd6 Ne4 14. Bc7 Nxc4 15. Ne5 Nxe5 16.
Bxe5 $14) 12. Rb1 Rb8 13. Qa4 {[%cal Rb1b7]} Qc7 14. Rfd1 Rhd8 {0-1 (42) De
Firmian, N (2520)-Short, N (2585) Wijk aan Zee 1986} 15. Nd2 $14) (7... O-O 8. d5
$1 {White takes the chance to gain the space advantage in the center. The game
is heading for a dubious version of the Benoni.} Bxc3 (8... exd5 $2 9. Nxd5
Nxd5 10. cxd5 d6 11. Bf4 {[%csl Rb4] when Black's bishop stands poorly on b4.})
9. bxc3 exd5 10. Nh4 d6 (10... Ne4 $6 11. cxd5 Nxc3 12. Qd3 Na4 13. Qc4 Qf6 14.
Ba3 b5 15. Qxb5 Nb6 16. Bb2 {1/2-1/2 (91) Martinovic,S (2526)-Drazic,S (2473)
Split 2013}) 11. cxd5 Nbd7 12. Nf5 Ne5 13. f4 Nc4 {1-0 (31) Miladinovic,I 
(2611)-Del Monaco,A (2218) Venice 2004} 14. e4 $16) 8. Qxd4 $1 Nc6 (8... O-O {
Is just a transposition.} 9. Rd1 Nc6 10. Qd3) 9. Qd3 O-O 10. Rd1 {As White's
central pressure is growing stronger Black needs to do its best to play d5.
Getting rid of the d pawn seems like a major goal for Black but, as we will
see, it doesn't warranty the equality.} Rc8 (10... Na5 11. b3 d5 12. cxd5 Rc8
13. Bb2 Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Qxd5 15. Qb1 Qh5 16. Qb2 $16 {1-0 (56) Kazhgaleyev,M 
(2594)-Asrian,K (2621) France 2008}) (10... Be7 11. b3 d5 (11... Rc8 12. Bb2
$14) 12. Qb1 Qc8 13. cxd5 exd5 (13... Nb4 14. d6 Bxd6 15. Rxd6 Qxc3 16. Bb2 Qc2
17. Qxc2 Nxc2 18. Rc1 $16) 14. Bb2 $16 {1-0 (30) Gaprindashvili,N (2475)
-Cuevas Rodriguez, M Hyeres 1988}) 11. b3 d5 {White consolidated c4 and is
ready to finish the development of his forces with Bb2. Black needs to react
immediately otherwise he will end up in a difficult position.} (11... Re8 12.
Bb2 Bf8 {0-1 (43) Olsen,P (2252)-Dragomarezkij,E (2471) Voronezh 2002} 13. Nb5
h6 (13... d5 14. Ng5 $1) 14. Nd6 $16) 12. cxd5 Ne5 13. Nxe5 Bxc3 14. Nc6 Bxc6
15. Qxc3 Nxd5 {½-½ (17) Miladinovic,I (2500)-Graf,A (2585) Kavala 1997} (
15... Bxd5 16. Qb4 $14 {1/2-1/2 (34) Haugli,P (2305)-Johansen,O (2336) ICCF
email 2007}) 16. Qe1 $1 $146 Qe7 17. a4 Rfd8 18. Ba3 Qb7 19. e4 Nf6 20. f3 $14
{[%csl Ga3,Gg2] The bishop pair gives White better chances.} *

