{Here I am going to explain the lines with an early ...d5. Black’s
intentions are very solid, trading central pawns and as many pieces as
possible to equalize smoothly. White has to be very precise in order to put
some pressure on his opponent's healthy position.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
Bb4 4. g3 c5 5. Nf3 Nc6 (5... d5 6. Bg2 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O {[%emt 0:00:10]
Transposes to Chapter}) (5... O-O 6. Bg2 d5 7. dxc5 {An attempt to punish
Black's move order.} ({The position gets extremely simplified after} 7. cxd5
Nxd5 8. Bd2 cxd4 9. Nxd5 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Qxd5 11. Qxd4 Qa5+ {And I found it
quite difficult to get any advantage for White.}) 7... dxc4 (7... Bxc5 8. cxd5
exd5 9. O-O Nc6 {Transposing to the Tarrasch Defense.}) 8. O-O Qa5 (8... Qxd1
9. Rxd1 Bxc5 10. Ne5 Nc6 11. Nxc4 $16 {1-0 (43) Ward,C (2480)-Bjornsson,T 
(2235) Reykjavik 1998:1-0 (43) Ward,C (2480)-Bjornsson,T (2235) Reykjavik 1998}
) 9. Qd4 Nc6 (9... Qxc5 10. Qxc5 Bxc5 11. Ne5 $14 {1-0 (35) Maze,S (2571)
-Rozentalis,E (2573) Mulhouse 2011}) 10. Qxc4 Qxc5 (10... Bxc5 11. a3 $14) (
10... e5 $2 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Bxc5 13. Ng5 g6 14. Qh4 h5 15. Bxc6 $1 bxc6
16. Ne4 {With a decisive advantage for White.}) 11. Qxc5 Bxc5 12. Bf4 $14 {
[%csl Gf4,Gg2] White's strong bishops and better development warranties him a
comfortable plus as happened in the game Rausis, I (2651)-Gascon del Nogal, J 
(2471) Sautron 2018.}) 6. Bg2 d5 7. O-O $1 {From my point of view, this
positional sacrifice is the most promising continuation for White} ({Trading
in the center is also a playable alternative} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bd2 cxd4 9. Nxd4
Nxd4 10. Nxd5 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 e5 {And Black gets good chances.}) 7... dxc4 ({
Few players would be happy to play} 7... O-O 8. cxd5 exd5 (8... Nxd5 $2 9. Nxd5
Qxd5 10. a3 Ba5 11. dxc5 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4]}) 9. Bg5 Be6 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Rc1
$14 {As it transposes to a favorable variation of the Tarrasch Defense.}) 8.
dxc5 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bxc5 10. Nd2 {White will certainly recover the sacrificed
pawn eventually but Black will try to put up maximum resistance and at least
exchange some minor pieces taking the game closer to the equality.} Na5 (10...
Ne5 11. Nde4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Be7 13. Bf4 f6 14. Bxe5 fxe5 15. Rac1 $16 {1-0 (27)
Colm,D-Guehrs,H Koblenz 1991}) (10... O-O 11. Nxc4 $14 {White's pressure makes
it difficult for Black to complete the development unharmed. 1-0 (43) Ward, C 
(2480)-Bjornsson, T (2235) Reykjavik 1998.}) 11. Nde4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Be7 13. Bd2
Nc6 14. Bc3 f6 15. Nd2 e5 {While White recovers the sacrificed pawn, Black
gains some space in the center and is close from completing the mobilization
of his forces.} 16. Nxc4 Be6 {We've reached the critical position of the
opening. White faces an interesting choice, gaining the bishop pair advantage
or clearing the path for his powerful light-squared bishop.} 17. Na5 $1 {
[%csl Gg2][%cal Gg2a8]} ({The bishop pair advantage didn't prove enough to win
after} 17. Nd6+ Bxd6 18. Rxd6 Ke7 19. Rad1 (19. Rdd1 Rhd8) 19... Rhd8 20. Rxd8
Rxd8 21. Rxd8 Kxd8 {1/2-1/2 (44) Radjabov,T (2746)-Polgar,J (2707) Biel 2007})
17... Nxa5 18. Bxa5 O-O 19. b3 Rab8 20. Bc7 Rbc8 21. Bd6 Kf7 22. Bxb7 Rc2 23.
Bxe7 Kxe7 24. Rac1 $16 {White had good winning chances in the game ½-½ (29)
Tikkanen, H (2550) -Shneider, A (2518) Cappelle-la-Grande 2011.} *

