{Now we will deal with the sharp 5.Nf3 Nc6 6.Bg2 Qa5.  In this variation Black
tries to punish White's ambitious setup with a combined pressure on c3 and d4.
To White's fortune, the position is full of dynamic resources to compensate
for the weakness of his pawn formation. White has to sacrifice a couple of
pawns in order to punish Black’s hazardous play. White’s compensation is
based on two main aspects, 1) The exposed situation of the Black Monarch and 2)
Black’s lack of development.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 c5 5. Nf3
Nc6 6. Bg2 Qa5 7. O-O Bxc3 ({In case of} 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bxc3 9. bxc3 {
the game takes another very different character.} O-O (9... Qxc3 $2 10. Nxc6
dxc6 (10... Qxa1 11. Qd6 dxc6 12. Ba3 $18) 11. Qd6 Bd7 12. Rb1 {1-0 (12) Meins,
G (2455)-Schumacher,O (2330) Bremen 1998}) 10. Qb3 d5 11. cxd5 {None of
Black's choices offers real equalizing chances.} Nxd4 (11... Nxd5 $2 12. Nxc6
bxc6 13. c4 $18) (11... exd5 12. Be3 Ne5 13. Rfd1 Bd7 14. a4 Rac8 15. Bf4 $14 {
1-0 (40) Taimanov,M-Sakharov,Y Tallinn (Estland) 1965}) 12. cxd4 exd5 13. Bf4
$14 {1-0 (58) Banikas,H (2637)-Kourkoulos Arditis,S (2294) Vrachati 2014}) 8.
bxc3 Qxc3 9. Bg5 $1 {In my opinion, this move is better than the old 9.Bf4
White's ideas are clearer after Bxf6 as Black's king feels weak in most lines.}
Nxd4 $146 {From the various ways to accept White's gambit this is the most
solid as Black strives to exchange as many pieces as possible.} ({It makes
sense to study} 9... Qxc4 $146 {as it's a solid alternative against 9.Bf4.} 10.
Bxf6 gxf6 11. Rc1 Qxa2 12. dxc5 {[%cal Gf3d2] Followed by Nd2. White's
compensation is more than enough for the sacrificed pawns.}) (9... cxd4 $6 {
This line is an inferior version of 9...Nxd4.} 10. Rc1 Qa5 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12.
Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Qe5 {1-0 (27) Kostelny,J (2198)-Hurtak,O (1987) Tatranske
Zruby 2015} 14. Qd3 O-O 15. Rb1 Rb8 16. Rb5 {With a dangerous initiative for
White.}) (9... Ne4 $2 {This move doesn't make sense and, as you will see, it
is almost losing for Black.} 10. Rc1 (10. d5 $146 Nxg5 (10... Nd4 $2 11. Rc1
Qa5 12. Nxd4 Nxg5 13. Nb3 Qd8 14. f4) (10... Nb8 11. dxe6 fxe6 12. Bf4 Nc6 13.
Rc1 Qf6 14. Qd3 $18) 11. Nxg5 Nd4 12. Ne4 Qc2 13. e3 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 Nf5 15. d6
$16) 10... Qa5 11. d5 Nxg5 12. Nxg5 Nd4 13. e3 Nf5 14. Qh5 g6 15. Qh3 h5 16. g4
Ng7 {1-0 (41) Battaglini,G (2172)-Pile,R (2059) Hyeres 2002} 17. Ne4 $16) 10.
Rc1 Nxf3+ 11. Bxf3 Qd4 $1 {This detail eases Black's problems. Even when
trading queens is, definitely, on Black's agenda, White will be able to
recover one of the sacrificed pawns and keep a strong pressure.} (11... Qe5 12.
Bf4 Qf5 (12... Qd4 $2 13. Qb3) 13. e4 Nxe4 14. Re1 Ng5 15. Bg4 Qg6 (15... Nh3+
16. Kf1) (15... Qf6 16. h4) 16. Re5 (16. h4 $2 h5) 16... h6 17. h4 Nh7 18. Rxc5
O-O 19. Bd6 Re8 20. Re5 Nf6 21. Bf3 $16) 12. Be3 (12. Qb3 Qd6 $1) 12... Qxd1
13. Rfxd1 O-O 14. Bxc5 Re8 15. g4 $1 h6 (15... d5 16. g5 Nd7 (16... Ne4 17. Be3
$16) 17. cxd5 Nxc5 18. Rxc5 exd5 19. Rc7 $16) 16. h4 $44 {[%csl Ra8,Gc5,Rc8,
Re8,Gf3] White's compensation for the sacrificed pawn is more than enough as
his strong bishop pair is added to Black's extreme lack of development.} *

