{In this chapter I'll cover a couple of very similar lines consisting of the
move ...Qc7. These lines may seem solid but are indeed very problematic for
Black.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 c5 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qc7 (6... a6
7. Bg2 Qc7 (7... Nc6 {In this line Black faces serious problems fighting for
the center and completing its development.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Bf4 $1 Re8 10. Nxc6
dxc6 (10... bxc6 11. Bd6 $1 Bxd6 12. Qxd6 Qe7 13. Qxe7 Rxe7 14. e4 Rb8 15. b3
e5 16. Rfd1 Kf8 17. c5 $16 {[%csl Rd7] The backward d-pawn left Black
struggling in the game 1-0 (40) Kasparov, G (2780)-Ricardi, P (2465) Buenos
Aires 1992}) 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Na4 Nd7 13. Rfd1 Re8 14. Bc7 $1 Be7 15. Rd2 $16
{[%cal Gd2d8] Black was defenseless against White's growing pressure along the
d-file in the game Gonzalez Garcia J.- Vega Garcia J., UNAM Mexico 2010.}) (
7... O-O 8. O-O Qc7 9. Na4) 8. O-O $1 {[%csl Yc4] This time it is not
necessary to defend c4 as it's taboo for Black.} O-O (8... Bxc3 {This
voluntary trade is very risky as it opens a3 for White's dark-squared bishop.}
9. bxc3 O-O 10. Ba3 d6 {1-0 (40) Vera Gonzalez Quevedo,R (2455)-Csom,I (2500)
Torremolinos (Malaga) 1981} 11. Qa4 $16) (8... Qxc4 $2 9. Bf4 Bxc3 10. Rc1 O-O
11. Rxc3 Qb4 12. Nxe6 $1 dxe6 13. Bd6 {White is winning Friedman-Chramov corr
1975}) 9. Na4 $1 d6 (9... Nc6 10. c5 d6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Qxd6 Qxd6 13. cxd6
Bxd6 14. Rd1 $18 {1-0 (21) Lesiege,A (2563)-Beaudoin,S (2072) Trois Rivieres
2004}) (9... Be7 10. Bf4 $146 d6 11. c5 $16) 10. a3 Bc5 11. b4 Ba7 {1-0 (41)
Czebe,A (2355)-Mochalov,E (2450) Zalakaros 1994} 12. Bb2 Nbd7 13. Rc1 $16 {
Black's lack of development leaves White with a clear advantage.}) 7. Qb3 $1 {
White defends c4 winning a tempo as Black is not willing to exchange his
dark-squared without anything in return.} Bc5 (7... Nc6 8. Nxc6 Bxc3+ (8...
Qxc6 $2 9. Qxb4 a5 10. Qa3 Qxh1 11. Nb5 $18 {1/2-1/2 (48) Carlsen,M (2570)
-Malakhov,V (2670) Khanty-Mansiysk 2005}) 9. Qxc3 Qxc6 10. f3 O-O 11. Bg5 $14 {
1-0 (43) Pereira Dos Santos,J-Blattner,K ICCF corr 1977}) 8. Be3 d6 {1-0 (49)
Ward,C (2500)-Arkell,K (2505) Swansea 1995} (8... a6 9. Na4 d6 10. Nxc5 dxc5
11. Nf3 e5 12. Bg2 O-O 13. O-O Re8 {1/2-1/2 (20) Nielsen,P (2644)-Anand,V 
(2792) Monte Carlo 2006} 14. Nd2 Nbd7 15. Nb1 $1 Rb8 16. Nc3 $16) 9. Ndb5 $1
$146 {[%csl Rd6] White would have gained access to d6 leaving Black's position
cramped and without counterplay.} Qe7 (9... Qc6 10. Bxc5 dxc5 11. Rg1 O-O 12.
O-O-O $16) 10. Bxc5 dxc5 11. O-O-O O-O 12. Bg2 $16 *

