{Now we will delve in the details of a line that may come from the English
opening. Let's see the most common move order to reach it from the mentioned
opening.} 1. d4 (1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. g3 Bb4
7. Bg2) 1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 c5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Bg2 cxd4 7. Nxd4 {
This line has plenty of transpositions to other lines of the Romanishin
variation and very often to the Tarrasch Defense.} O-O {Black could try to
complicate the game with some active moves.} (7... Ne5 8. Qb3 Bc5 9. Be3 $146 {
[%cal Gd4e6] This active move creates problems for Black as White threatens
Nxe6.} d6 10. Rd1 $16) (7... Qb6 8. Nb3 Qa6 {This artificial sequence of queen
moves is quite popular; but, in my view, it is not advisable for Black.} (8...
Ne5 9. c5 $1 {Sacrificing pawns is perhaps the most important device White
uses in these positions. The initiative and positional features are way more
important than pawns in the Romanishin variation.} Bxc5 10. Nxc5 Qxc5 11. O-O
d5 12. e4 dxe4 (12... d4 13. Na4) 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 O-O 15. Bf4 $14 {
1-0 (28) Illescas Cordoba,M (2600)-Yudasin,L (2635) Pamplona 1992}) 9. c5 b6
10. O-O $1 bxc5 (10... Bb7 11. Bg5 Bxc3 12. bxc3 Ne5 13. Bxb7 Qxb7 14. Bxf6
gxf6 15. Qd4 $36 {1-0 (41) Gleizerov,E (2405)-Dvoirys,S (2450) Voronezh 1988})
11. Be3 d5 12. Nxc5 Qa5 13. N3a4 Qb5 14. a3 Ba5 15. b4 Bd8 16. Nc3 Qb8 17. Qa4
$18 {1-0 (30) Eingorn,V (2475)-Georgiev,K (2430) Lvov (Ukraine) 1984}) (7...
Qa5 8. O-O {Transposes to 6...Qa5 7.0-0 cxd4 8.Nxd4}) 8. O-O d5 {After this
move, the game reaches the Tarrasch Defense with the difference of Black
having the dark-squared bishop on b4 rather than on e7. As trading this bishop
for the knight on c3 is not such an appealing idea, most of the time, it will
have to move back at some point. Due to these reasons, I am convinced that
White should get an edge in these lines.} (8... a6 9. Bf4 {Transposes to 6...
a6 7.Bg2 Nc6 8.00 00 9.Bf4.}) (8... Qb6 9. Nb3) ({A lot of respectable
grandmasters have tried} 8... Ne5 9. Qb3 Be7 (9... Qe7 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bxf6 gxf6
12. Nf5 $1 $18 {1-0 (80) Gallego Alcaraz,A (2461)-Maghsoodloo,P (2594) Moscow
2018}) (9... Qa5 {Black's artificial set-up is deemed to failure.} 10. Bd2 Nc6
11. Nc2 $1 Be7 12. Ne4 Qh5 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. Bf3 Qg6 15. Bc3 $16 {White's
much better development and good control of the center gave him a clear
advantage in the game ½-½ (75) Neiksans, A (2622)-Miezis, N (2506) Riga 2016})
(9... Bc5 10. Be3 d6 11. Na4 Nfg4 12. Nxc5 dxc5 13. Nb5 a6 14. Rfd1 Qb6 15. Rd6
Nc6 16. Nc3 $16 {1-0 (55) Mastrovasilis,A (2526)-Tsolakidou,S (2240) Vrachati
2014}) 10. Rd1 a6 {1-0 (59) Ivanchuk,V (2787)-Ponomariov,R (2705) Moscow 2007}
11. Na4 $146 Qc7 12. Bf4 Nh5 13. Bxe5 Qxe5 14. c5 $1 {A fine detail of White's
strategy now Black's queenside is almost frozen.} Bxc5 15. Nf3 Qc7 16. Rac1 d6
17. Nxc5 dxc5 18. Qe3 $18 {When Black's immobilized army leads to disaster.}) (
8... h6 {It seems that Black wants to play ...d5 without having to deal with
Bg5.} 9. Bf4 $1 d5 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Rc1 Bg4 12. h3 Be6 13. a3 Ba5 14. Na4 $16
{1-0 (33) Khenkin,I (2550)-Zolnierowicz,K (2385) Krynica 1997}) 9. cxd5 exd5 (
9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Be3 {White's game is very promising in this kind
of IQP middle game as the position is getting simplified and Black has no
initiative.} Be6 12. Rc1 Qd7 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Qa4 $18 {1-0 (39) Schlosser,P 
(2505)-Fahnenschmidt,G (2336) Leinfelden 2000}) 10. Bg5 Be6 (10... Bxc3 11.
bxc3 Be6 12. Rb1 Na5 13. Rb5 a6 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Rb4 $18 {Black's position is
hopeless and the material is even. 1-0 (26) Kasparov,G (2735)-Arlandi,E (2380)
Cannes 1988}) ({After} 10... Be7 {White has an extra tempo compared to the
mainline of the Tarrasch Defense, which obviously leads to a White advantage
almost with any of the available lines.} 11. Rc1 h6 12. Be3 Re8 13. Qc2 Bf8 14.
Rfd1 $16 {1-0 (33) Tukmakov,V (2560)-Damjanovic,M (2455) Vilnius (Lithuania)
1978}) 11. Rc1 h6 12. Be3 Na5 13. Qa4 $14 {1/2-1/2 (29) Prange,S (2190)-Keller,
T (2215) Germany 1997} *

