{In this chapter I will explain a very popular line that has been played by
many strong players. Fortunately for our cause White is able to keep the
initiative with a very nice pawn sacrifice.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4.
g3 c5 5. Nf3 Ne4 6. Qd3 Qa5 7. Qxe4 Bxc3+ 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 Nc6 (9... cxd4
10. Qxd4 O-O 11. Bg2 Nc6 12. Qd6 $14) (9... Qb6 {This is how Karpov reacted to
Kasparov's opening surprise in the first game of their 1985 World Championship
Match.} 10. dxc5 $1 Qxb2 11. Rb1 Qc3 (11... Qxa2 $6 {This second capture is
too risky.} 12. Qe5 $1 O-O 13. Qc3 {With this fine maneuver the White queen
dramatically restricts its counterpart's possibilities.} Qa4 (13... Qa6 14. Bg2
d5 15. O-O {and Black would be under strong pressure.}) 14. Bg2 Nc6 15. O-O Qa5
{1/2-1/2 (17) Reinecke,R-Langen,R Germany 1987} (15... f5 16. Rb5 a6 17. Rb6
Qa5 18. Qe3 $16 {1-0 (32) Rantanen,M-Hannula,H Finland 1986}) 16. Qxa5 $146
Nxa5 17. Ra1 Nc6 18. Ne4 f5 19. Nd6 g5 20. Ra3 {While White keeps building the
pressure on the queenside, Black's position lacks counterplay.}) (11... Qa3 12.
Qd4 $1 O-O 13. Bg2 Na6 (13... Nc6 14. Qd6 b6 (14... Qxa2 15. O-O Qa5 {0-1 (45)
Laczay,I (1528)-Gyimesi,J (2037) LSS email 2011} 16. Ra1 Qc3 17. Rfc1 Qd4 18.
Bxc6 Qxd6 19. cxd6 bxc6 20. c5 $16) 15. O-O bxc5 {0-1 (39) Fischdick,G (2275)
-Hennig,D (2335) Germany 1990} 16. Ne4 $16) 14. Ne4 f5 (14... Qa5+ 15. Qd2 Qc7
(15... Qxd2+ 16. Kxd2 f5 17. Nd6 Nxc5 18. Rb5 Ne4+ 19. Bxe4 fxe4 20. Rc5 $18)
16. Rb5 Rb8 17. Qd4 b6 18. cxb6 Rxb6 19. Rg5 e5 20. Qxe5 Qxe5 21. Rxe5 $16 {
1/2-1/2 (77) Bluvshtein,M (2611)-Riazantsev,A (2688) Khanty-Mansiysk 2011}) 15.
Nd6 Rb8 16. O-O Qxc5 {1-0 (23) Zhikharev,V-Meshkov,Y USSR 1987} 17. e3 $14 {
White has more than enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn.}) 12. Qd3 Qxd3
13. exd3 Na6 14. d4 (14. Rb5 $5) 14... Rb8 15. Bg2 Ke7 16. Ke2 Rd8 (16... b6
17. cxb6 axb6 18. Rb3 Bb7 19. Bxb7 Rxb7 20. Rhb1 Nc7 (20... Rhb8 21. c5 b5 22.
Nc4 $18) 21. Rxb6 Rxb6 22. Rxb6 Ra8 23. Rb2 Ra4 24. Kd3 $16 {Kasparov}) 17. Ne4
b6 18. Nd6 Nc7 (18... bxc5 19. Rxb8 Nxb8 20. dxc5 $16) 19. Rb4 Ne8 20. Nxe8
Kxe8 21. Rhb1 {And White's pressure gave Kasparov an important victory in the
mentioned game. 1-0 (42) Kasparov,G (2700)-Karpov,A (2720) Moscow (Russia) 1985
}) 10. d5 $5 {This advance leads to a very promising pawn sacrifice and is
White's most critical try.} Nd4 11. Bg2 Nb3 ({The alternatives steer the game
into calm waters where White keeps an undisputed edge:} 11... d6 12. Qd3 e5 13.
O-O O-O 14. e3 Nf5 15. a3 $14 {1/2-1/2 (45) Lenic,L (2569)-Adamski,J (2307)
Warsaw 2008}) (11... O-O 12. Qd3 exd5 13. Bxd5 d6 14. O-O {[%csl Rc5,Rd6]
White's superior pawn structure secures an advantage.} Bf5 (14... Be6 15. Be4
h6 16. Nf3 (16. e3 $5 Nc6 17. f4) 16... Qb4 (16... Qa6) 17. b3 f5 18. Nxd4 fxe4
19. Qxe4 Bh3 20. Qd5+ Kh8 21. Nb5 Bxf1 22. Rxf1 {White obtained a powerful
compensation for the sacrificed exchange in Romanishin, O (2595)-Tal, M (2620)
Tallinn (Estland) 1977}) 15. Be4 Bxe4 16. Nxe4 Rae8 (16... Qb4 17. e3 Ne6 18.
Nc3 Rab8 19. Rab1 Rfd8 20. Nd5 Qa5 21. a3 $14 {1-0 (74) Kazhgaleyev,M (2602)
-Zhou,W (2416) Hyderabad 2005}) 17. e3 Nf3+ (17... Nc6 18. Nxd6 Rd8 19. Rfd1
Rd7 20. Qb3 Qc7 21. Nb5 $16 {1/2-1/2 (60) Berkes,F (2650)-Sulskis,S (2535)
Hastings 2016}) 18. Kg2 Ne5 19. Qd5 Re6 {1/2-1/2 (28) Vachier Lagrave,M (2722)
-Van Wely,L (2701) Linares 2013} 20. b3 $14) 12. Rd1 Qxa2 ({Trading the
knights before taking the pawn leaves White with overwhelming pressure.} 12...
Nxd2 13. Rxd2 Qxa2 (13... O-O 14. Qf4 Rd8 15. b3 $14 {And Oleg Romanishin had
to pay the price of being on the wrong side of the board! 1-0 (38) Petkov,V 
(2429)-Romanishin,O (2503) Figueira da Foz 2009}) 14. O-O O-O 15. dxe6 fxe6 (
15... dxe6 16. Qe5 $1 Qa5 (16... Qxc4 17. Rfd1 $18 {[%cal Gd2d8] Ward,C (2431)
-Buckley,D (2266) England 2016. Black is helpless against Rd8.}) 17. Rfd1 f6
18. Qd6 Re8 (18... Qb6 19. Qe7 $18 {White wins on the spot.}) 19. Be4 Qb6 {
1-0 (40) Sedlak,N (2553)-Lenic,L (2569) Murska Sobota 2008} 20. Qf4 $16 {
White's control of the board is undisputable.}) 16. Rfd1 Qb3 17. Qh4 Rf6 18.
Be4 h6 19. Bc2 Qb4 20. Qe4 $18 {1-0 (28) Rogers,I (2510)-Lau,R (2460) Dortmund
1985}) 13. dxe6 dxe6 (13... fxe6 14. Qe5 O-O 15. Qc3 Nxd2 16. Rxd2 Rb8 17. O-O
b5 18. b3 Qa6 19. Qe5 $14 {1/2-1/2 (31) Kuzubov,Y (2568)-Lysyj,I (2578)
Hengelo 2007}) 14. Qe5 O-O 15. O-O Nd4 (15... f6 16. Qc3 Nd4 17. Kh1 $1 {
A nice detail that may have escaped Black's attention.} Qa6 ({Capturing the
e-pawn would lead to an immediate victory for White.} 17... Nxe2 $2 18. Qe3 Nd4
19. Ra1 Qxb2 20. Rfb1 Qc2 21. Be4 $18) 18. b4 e5 19. bxc5 $18 {0-1 (40)
Kuzubov,Y (2559)-Moranda,W (2462) Batumi 2006}) (15... Nxd2 16. Rxd2 Qxc4 17.
Rfd1 $18 {Ward,C (2431)-Buckley,D (2266) England 2016. Black is helpless
against Rd8.}) 16. e3 Nb3 17. Nxb3 Qxb3 18. Rd6 Qb4 19. Rfd1 $16 {And once
again White's pressure is overwhelming. 1-0 (35) Kazhgaleyev, M (2606)
-Fedorchuk, S (2592) Paris 2006.} *

