{In this chapter, I will cover two lines, one is very solid for Black 8...Nxc3
and the riskier 8...Qf5. In the solid one, Black is close to equalizing, but
as usual, ends up struggling to make a draw. The riskier line leads to a more
interesting battle, albeit, objectively speaking, Black must stand a bit worse.
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 c5 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Ne4 7. Qd3 Qa5 8.
Nb3 Nxc3 (8... Qf5 {With this continuation Black strives for a complicated
battle.} 9. Qe3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Be7 11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gd7d6,
Ge6e5] We reached the critical position of the 8...Qf5 variation. Black is
ready to complete its queenside development with ...b6 or ...d6 followed by ...
e5. White's most popular choice is the logical 13.c5 but as Black is able to
get a very decent position, I'd like to recommend the cunning} 13. a4 $1 (13.
c5 b6 $1 {Black plays it anyway as none of the possible responses give White
an edge.} 14. cxb6 (14. Nd4 Qxc5 15. Nxc6 dxc6 16. Qxc5 bxc5 (16... Bxc5 17.
Bxc6) 17. Bxc6 Rb8 {is about equal as was played in the game (33) Mesropov,K 
(2474)-Grigoryev,V (2513) ICCF (RCCA) 2003}) 14... axb6 15. Qxb6 Ba6 $132)
13... Ne5 (13... d6 14. a5 {[%cal Ga5a6] Threatening a6} a6 (14... e5 15. a6)
15. Nd4 $14) ({Now the intended} 13... b6 14. a5 Rb8 15. axb6 axb6 (15... Rxb6
16. Nd4 $14) 16. Qf4 {leaves Black under pressure.}) 14. c5 d5 15. cxd6 Bxd6 {
1/2-1/2 (28) Berglund,P-Goransson,G Sweden 1988} 16. a5 $1 a6 17. Qd4 Be7 18.
Ba3 $16 {And it is very hard to deal with White's queenside pressure.}) 9. Bd2
$1 Ne4 ({The alternative} 9... Qe5 {leaves White on top.} 10. bxc3 Be7 11. Bf4
Qf6 12. Bg2 Nc6 13. O-O O-O {0-1 (57) Vojinovic, G (2440)-Certic, B (2435) Nis
1995} 14. Rab1 $14 {With the usual annoying pressure.}) 10. Qxe4 Bxd2+ 11. Nxd2
Nc6 12. Bg2 O-O {[#]} 13. Qd3 $1 {[%csl Gd5] From the various ways to prepare
castling, this is the most precise as it controls d5. Black's best chance is
to sacrifice a pawn for the sake of freeing its position.} d5 $1 (13... Qe5 14.
Rb1 Rd8 (14... Nb4 15. Qb3 (15. Qc3 Qxc3 16. bxc3 Na6 17. O-O Rb8 {0-1 (64)
Rossiter,P (2270)-Arkell,K (2455) Isle of Man 1993} 18. Rb3 b6 (18... Nc5 19.
Ra3 a6 20. Nb3 $16) 19. Ra3) 15... a5 16. Qc3 f6 {1/2-1/2 (32) Suba,M (2465)
-Ftacnik,L (2545) Prague 1985} 17. Qxe5 fxe5 18. O-O Nxa2 19. c5 $16) (14... d5
15. O-O Rd8 16. Rfd1 Qf6 {transposes.}) 15. O-O d5 16. Rfd1 Qf6 (16... h6 17.
Nb3 Rb8 18. Nd4 Bd7 19. cxd5 exd5 20. Rd2 $14 {1-0 (67) Overton,D (2444)
-Staroske,U (2442) ICCF email 2009}) 17. b4 $5 dxc4 18. Qxc4 Rd4 19. Qc5 Qd8
20. e3 Rd6 (20... Rxd2 21. Rxd2 Qxd2 22. Bxc6 bxc6 23. Qxc6 $18) 21. b5 Na5 22.
Bf3 b6 23. Qxd6 Qxd6 24. Nb3 Qxd1+ 25. Rxd1 Bb7 26. Bxb7 Nxb7 27. Rd7 $16 {
1-0 (47) Landa,K (2678)-Ftacnik,L (2553) Germany 2008}) (13... Ne5 14. Qd4 Nc6
15. Qd6 Qb6 16. Rb1 Nb4 17. Qxb6 axb6 18. a3 Nc2+ 19. Kf1 Nd4 20. e3 Nc6 21.
Ke2 $16 {[%csl Rb6,Rb7,Rd7] Black's pawn structure is horrible as a result of
having doubled pawns and a backward in an open file. ½-½ (31) Cunningham,
P-Williams,A Cardiff 1979}) (13... Nb4 {Doesn't make sense.} 14. Qc3) ({
Preparing ...d5 with} 13... Rd8 {[%cal Gd7d5] doesn't improve Black's chances
of equalizing.} 14. Qd6 Qb4 15. Qxb4 Nxb4 16. O-O d5 17. a3 Nc6 18. Rfd1 $16)
14. cxd5 exd5 (14... Rd8 {Illescas Cordoba,M (2598)-Moreno Ruiz,J (2466)
Ayamonte 2007} 15. d6 $1 $146 Qb4 (15... Ne5 16. Qd4 Nc6 17. Qc3 Qxc3 18. bxc3
Rxd6 19. O-O-O $14) 16. Rc1 Rxd6 (16... Qxb2 17. O-O) 17. Qc3 $14) 15. Qxd5 $1
{Accepting the pawn is in my opinion the best way to fight for an advantage.} (
15. O-O Qb6 16. Nb3 Bg4 $132) 15... Qb4 16. Qb3 Be6 17. Qxb4 Nxb4 18. O-O Nxa2
{[#]} (18... Rad8 19. Ne4 b6 20. a3 Nc2 21. Rac1 Nd4 22. Rfe1 $16 {1/2-1/2 (60)
Taras,I-Pecis,G (2346) ICCF email 2005}) {White has very good practical
chances with the tricky} 19. f4 $5 $146 Rfd8 20. Rfd1 {[%csl Ra2,Ge2][%cal
Gg2a8] Among White's various trumps we can count the long diagonal pressure,
the central pawns and the awkward situation of Black's knight.} Rab8 $1 {
Sacrificing the knight seems to be the best chance for Black.} (20... Nb4 21.
Bxb7 Nc2 (21... Rab8 22. Ne4 $16) 22. Bxa8 Nxa1 23. Be4 Nb3 24. Bd3 Nc5 25. Bc2
$16 {The extra pawn gives White excellent winning chances.}) 21. f5 Bxf5 22.
Rxa2 Bc2 23. Rc1 Rxd2 24. b3 Rd1+ 25. Rxd1 Bxd1 26. Bd5 Rc8 27. Rxa7 Bxe2 28.
Rxb7 $16 {The position got simplified a lot but Black is still under pressure.}
*

