{In this Chapter we'll cover one of the most prestigious lines for Black
against the Romanishin variation. In it, Black is happy to trade a knight for
White's dark-squared bishop paying the price of being left with a cramped
position. White keeps good control of the most important central squares, some
pressure along the d-file and along the long diagonal. But it's quite
difficult to get more as Black's position has no weaknesses and, in the
long-term, his bishop pair may become an important asset.  As we will see
White has some active plans that may put Black under strong pressure.} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 c5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Ne4 7. Bd2 Nxd2 8. Qxd2 cxd4
9. Nxd4 Ne5 {Provoking b3 is a way for Black to improve the scope of its
dark-squared bishop.} (9... Nxd4 {Black is fighting for a draw right from the
opening.} 10. Qxd4 Qf6 (10... O-O 11. O-O $14) 11. Qe3 $146 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Rb8
13. O-O b6 14. c5 O-O (14... Bb7 $2 15. cxb6 Bxg2 16. bxa7) 15. Rfd1 Qe7 (15...
Qf5 16. Rab1) 16. Rab1 $16) (9... Qb6 {Is another popular alternative.} 10. Nc2
(10. e3 $5 Ne5 11. b3 Qa5 12. Rc1 a6 13. O-O O-O 14. a3 $1 Be7 (14... Qxa3 15.
Ra1 Bxc3 16. Qxc3 Qc5 (16... Qe7 17. c5 $14) 17. Ra5 Qc7 {1/2-1/2 (38)
Riedener,T (2394)-Perez Fernandez,J (2409) ICCF email 2011} 18. Nxe6 dxe6 19.
Qxe5 Qxe5 20. Rxe5 $14) (14... Bxa3 15. Ra1 Qc5 16. Ne4 Bb4 17. Nxc5 Bxd2 18.
Nxb7 $14) 15. f4 Ng4 16. b4 Qc7 {1-0 (47) Eldridge,M (2344)-Geissler,W (2304)
ICCF email 2011} 17. Qe2 Nf6 18. g4 $40) 10... Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. b3 $5 (12.
Rab1 d6 13. Rfd1 Rd8 14. Ne3 a6 15. b4 Qa7 16. a4 Bd7 17. a5 $14) 12... Rd8 13.
Rad1 d6 14. Kh1 Ne5 $6 15. Ne3 Bf8 16. f4 Ng6 {1:0. Gonzalez Garcia - Blanco
Fernández, Mexican Championship 2014.} 17. Ned5 $1 exd5 18. Nxd5 Qc5 19. b4
Qxc4 20. Rc1 $18) (9... O-O {In this way Black doesn't commit too soon with
his knight keeping some extra options available.} 10. Nc2 Be7 11. O-O a6 12.
Rfd1 Qc7 13. Rac1 d6 $146 {This move was pointed out as an improvement by Roiz
in his excellent book about the Nimzowitsch Indian.} ({Let's see why there was
the need for improvement by Black:} 13... Rd8 14. Ne3 Qa5 (14... d6 $2 15.
Ncd5 $1 $16) 15. a3 d6 16. b4 Qh5 {Was played in Farago,I (2485)-Suba,M (2500)
Baile Herculane 1982, now White stands better after} 17. f4 $14) {Now let's
see how the game may continue,} 14. Ne3 Ne5 15. f4 Nd7 (15... Nxc4 $2 16. Nxc4
Qxc4 17. Nd5) 16. b4 {Deviating from the mentioned source.} (16. Ne4 Rd8 {
Black is ok according to Roiz.}) 16... Nf6 (16... Rb8 17. Ne4 Rd8 18. f5 Ne5
19. Rf1 $36) 17. g4 $1 h6 (17... Qb6 18. Kh1 Qxb4 $4 19. Ncd5 $18) (17... Bd7
18. c5 dxc5 (18... d5 19. g5 Nh5 20. Nexd5 exd5 21. Nxd5 Qd8 22. Nxe7+ Qxe7 23.
Qxd7 $18) 19. g5) 18. g5 hxg5 19. fxg5 Nd7 (19... Ne8 20. Ne4) (19... Nh7 20.
h4) 20. Ng4 $36) 10. Nc2 Be7 ({The complications arising after} 10... Nxc4 11.
Qd4 Bxc3+ 12. Qxc3 Qa5 13. b4 Qc7 {lead to a clearly better position for White.
