{In this chapter we will deal with a couple of solid lines, 9...Qb6 almost was
considered the main line in the nineties and 9...Na6.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 c5 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O 7. Bg2 d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Qb3 $1 {
This move popularized by Vadim Zvjaginsev in the early nineties is today the
indisputable mainline.} Qb6 {This active move leads to a variety of
complications, yet with accurate play, White is always on top.} (9... Na6 {
[%cal Gd5c3,Ga6c5] With this curious move Black prepares Nxc3. The knight is
misplaced but soon will have the possibility to move to c5.} 10. O-O Nxc3 ({
The alternative} 10... Nc5 {forces White to play with precision} 11. Qc2 $1 (
11. Qc4 Bxc3 12. bxc3 b6 {Looks good for Black. 1-0 (66) Atalik, S (2535)
-Tzoumbas,A (2415) Peristeri 1994}) 11... Bxc3 12. bxc3 Bd7 {[%cal Ga8c8]} 13.
c4 $1 {Just when Black was getting ready to put White's c-pawn under pressure
with Rc8, it takes a step forward and allows White to get a fearsome
initiative.} Ne7 (13... Ba4 14. Nb3 Rc8 15. Ba3 b5 (15... Nf6 16. Qc3 Nfd7 17.
Nxc5 Nxc5 18. Bxc5 Rxc5 19. Qb4 Qa5 20. Qxa5 Rxa5 21. Bxb7 $16) 16. Qb1 Bxb3
17. axb3 bxc4 18. bxc4 Nb6 19. Qc2 $16 {1-0 (47) Gofshtein,L (2509)-Eames,R 
(2311) Hastings 2006}) 14. Ba3 Qc7 {1-0 (23) Nielsen,P (2578)-Kishnev,S (2495)
Germany 2001} 15. Nb3 $16 {[%csl Ga3] White's dark-squared bishop is causing
Black severe troubles.}) 11. bxc3 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Yb4c5,Ya6c5] Now Black has
to decide which piece belongs to c5. Of course, the knight looks like the
normal answer, as otherwise, it would have to stay on a6.} Be7 ({Even though} 
11... Bc5 {has plenty of supporters. The idea is to avoid the forced lines
that occur after 11...Nc5 and to try to keep the pawn structure intact in the
hope of completing the development slowly.} 12. Qb5 $5 {[%cal Gd4b3] This
odd-looking move prepares Nb3 and keeps Black's queenside under pressure.} ({
Another worthy alternative is} 12. Nf3 Qe7 13. Rd1 Re8 (13... e5 14. Qd5 e4 (
14... Re8 15. Qxe5 $1 Qxe5 16. Nxe5 Rxe5 17. Rd8+ Bf8 18. Ba3 Nc5 19. f4 Rh5
20. Rad1 $18) 15. Nd4 Re8 16. Bg5 $14) 14. Bf4 f6 15. e4 b6 16. e5 $14 {
½-½ (25) Lekic, D (2396)-Ruck, R (2570) Rijeka 2010.}) 12... Qc7 (12... Qe7 13.
Nb3 Bd6 14. Bg5 f6 15. Be3 Nc7 16. Qd3 Nd5 {1/2-1/2 (55) Smirnov,A (2460)
-Zhigalko,S (2592) St Petersburg 2008} 17. Bd4 $14) 13. Nb3 Rb8 14. Rd1 e5 (
14... b6 15. Nd4 Bb7 16. Bf4 e5 17. Bxb7 Rxb7 18. Bxe5 Qxe5 19. Qxa6 Rd7 20.
Nf3 Qxc3 21. Rxd7 Qxa1+ 22. Kg2 $16 {1-0 (118) Jovanic,O (2527)-Hulak,K (2532)
Rijeka 2009}) 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 16. Ba3 b6 {1/2-1/2 (31) Agrest,E (2561)-Tiviakov,
S (2663) Dresden 2007} 17. Bxc5 bxc5 (17... Qxc5 18. Qxc5 bxc5 19. Rd5 $16) 18.
Qc4 $14) 12. Rd1 Nc5 13. Qc4 $1 e5 (13... Bd7 14. Ba3 Qc8 (14... Rc8 $2 15. Nc6
$1 {This is the way to justify White's previous moves.} Bxc6 (15... bxc6 16.
Bxc5 $16) 16. Rxd8 Rfxd8 {1-0 (60) Nielsen,P (2640)-Vijayalakshmi,S (2417)
