{In this chapter, I will examine a popular main line where the Black pawn
structure gets weakened in return for obtaining dangerous piece activity with
the Nd5 being especially annoying for White.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4.
g3 c5 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O 7. Bg2 d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Qb3 Nc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6
11. O-O Rb8 $5 {Seeking activity is Black's way to compensate for the damages
in his pawn structure.} (11... a5 12. Rd1 Qe7 13. Na4 Ba6 14. Qc2 Bd6 15. a3 (
15. Qxc6 Rfc8) 15... f5 {1/2-1/2 (28) Barsov,A (2550)-Naumkin,I (2436) Porto
San Giorgio 2002} 16. e3 $14) (11... Qb6 $6 12. Na4 Qb5 13. a3 Ba5 (13... Be7
14. Qxb5 cxb5 15. Bxd5 exd5 16. Nc3 Bb7 17. Rd1 $16) 14. Qc2 Bb6 $4 15. Be4 Ba6
16. Bd3 $18 {Nielsen - Stefansson, 1997.}) (11... Be7 $6 12. Rd1 Ba6 13. e4 Rb8
14. exd5 $1 Rxb3 15. axb3 cxd5 16. Rxa6 $16 {Khalifman - Epishin, 1996.}) 12.
a3 {Almost forcing ...Nxc3 as the retreat ...Bd6 leaves Black's dark-squared
bishop exposed to Ne4.} Nxc3 {The resulting positions after this move are, in
general, very close to equality. However, as we'll see only two results are
possible. Black has to be very accurate to draw the game.} ({As I explained
before, Black's dark-squared bishop is exposed on d6.} 12... Bd6 {[%csl Rd6]}
13. Qc2 Ba6 (13... Nxc3 14. Qxc3 Ba6 15. Rd1 (15. b4 $5 $146 Bxe2 16. Re1 Bb5
17. Bb2 e5 18. Rac1 $44) 15... Bxe2 16. Rd2 (16. Re1) 16... Bb5 17. a4 Ba6 18.
Qxc6 Rb6 19. Qc2 Qc7 20. a5 Rb4 21. Qxc7 Bxc7 22. Rc2 Be5 23. Be3 $14 {1/2-1/2
(59) Mamutov,S (2172)-Dunlop,G (2132) ICCF email 2011}) 14. Ne4 Be7 15. b4 Bb5
16. Nc5 {White has an edge.} a5 17. bxa5 Qxa5 $2 ({It was better to continue
with} 17... Bxc5 18. Qxc5 Qxa5 19. Bf3 $14) 18. Nd7 Ba4 19. Qd2 Qxd2 20. Bxd2
Rb2 21. Bc1 Rxe2 22. Nxf8 Kxf8 23. Bf3 $16 {White was almost winning in ½-½ 
(80) Wojtaszek,R (2637)-Papaioannou,I (2624) Kallithea 2009}) 13. bxc3 Bd6 14.
Qa4 Qc7 15. Qxc6 Qxc6 16. Bxc6 {[#]} {Now we've reached the critical position
of the 11...Rb8 variation. After a semi-forced featured sequence, Black is a
pawn down but is very close to equality. Is there a way for White to get a
long-lasting pressure even at the price of returning the pawn?} Rb3 $1 {
Black is on the right track to equalize. But as there are some attacking
resources is still to soon to call it a day.} (16... Ba6 {As will soon become
clear this move harms Black chances.} 17. Bf3 Rb3 (17... Rfc8 18. Rd1 Be5 {
1-0 (37) Levin,F (2475)-Mikhalevski,A (2470) Budapest 1997} 19. Be3 Bxc3 20.
Rac1 Bb2 21. Rxc8+ Rxc8 22. Rd7 $16) 18. Rd1 Bc5 (18... Be5 19. Be3 Rxc3 (19...
Bxc3 20. Rab1 $16) 20. Rac1 $16) 19. Be3 Bxe3 20. fxe3 Rxc3 21. Rd7 Rxe3 22.
Kf2 Rb3 23. Rxa7 $18 {1-0 (37) Atalik,S (2525)-Ulybin,M (2550) Beijing 1996.})
({The weakening} 16... a5 {is better for White after} 17. Rd1 Be7 {1/2-1/2 (27)
Collas,S (2333)-Milliet,S (2367) Belfort 2010} 18. Be3 Rb3 19. c4 Rxa3 20. Rxa3
Bxa3 21. Bb5 {[%cal Gc4c5,Gc5c6,Gc6c7] And the threatening advance of the c
