{In this chapter, we'll deal with the line that is considered the most solid
continuation for Black. Similarly to the previous chapter, here Black lacks
chances to fight for the whole point; and for this reason, the perspective of
playing this line as White is very pleasant.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4.
g3 c5 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O 7. Bg2 d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Qb3 Qa5 10. Bd2 Nc6 11.
Nxc6 bxc6 12. O-O Bxc3 (12... Nxc3 $6 13. Bxc3 Bxc3 14. Bxc6 $1 Ba6 15. Bxa8
Bxe2 16. Rfb1 Bd4 17. Be4 $1 $146 (17. Bf3 $146 Qf5 18. Kg2 $14)) (12... Ba6 $2
13. Nxd5 Bxd2 14. Ne7+ Kh8 15. Nxc6 $16) (12... Rb8 $4 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. a3 $18
) 13. bxc3 {[%csl Gd2,Gg2] We have reached a position with an almost
symetrical pawn structure where the bishop pair promises a slight plus for
White.} Ba6 14. Rfd1 {[#]} Qc5 $1 {[%csl Gc4] Black holds a firm grip over c4.
The alternatives clearly favour White:} (14... Bxe2 $2 15. c4 Bxd1 16. Qxd1 Qa3
