{This chapter covers a line that has an enormous theoretical significance,
because of its existence White can play 4.g3 and fight for an opening
advantage. To avoid releasing the central tension, White needs to sacrifice a
pawn. The game resembles very much a Catalan gambit. The idea is not new as it
has been played for decades, but only recently did it become popular among
high-level grandmasters.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d5 {
The lines arising after this move have a very close connection with the
Catalan Opening and sometimes may even transpose to it with the particularity
of White having played an extra a3 for free.} 6. Nf3 {After this move White is
ready to sacrifice a pawn with the idea to pursue higher positional assets to
build a powerful pressure.} dxc4 {Although this is the most principled move,
White has to pay attention to other alternatives:} ({Black may refrain from
going into a theoretical debate and try to play in the style of the Catalan's
closed variation} 6... c6 $5 7. O-O Nbd7 (7... b6 8. Ne5 Bb7 9. Bg5 Be7 10. Qa4
$14) 8. Qb3 $1 {[%cal Gb3c4,Rb3b4] An important detail, as White not only
defends c4 but also attacks the enemy's bishop at the same time.} Bd6 (8... Be7
9. Rd1 b6 10. Ne5 Bb7 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. e4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Bxe4 Rfd8 15.
Be3 Qc7 16. Rac1 e5 17. c5 $1 {As usual in the Catalan opening, White is much
better after this move. 1-0 (41) Harikrishna, P (2673)-Lopez Martinez, J (2540)
Gibraltar 2009}) (8... Bxc3 9. bxc3 $14) (8... Qe7 9. Bf4 b6 10. Ne5 Bb7 11.
Nxd7 Nxd7 12. Rac1 $14) 9. Rd1 $1 ({It was premature to play} 9. e4 {at once}
Nxe4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Ng5 Nf6 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 e5 $11) 9... b6 (9... Qe7
10. e4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Ng5 f5 13. c5) (9... Re8 {½-½ (32) Kurajica,B 
(2507)-Soko,M (2105) Zenica 2013} 10. e4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Ng5 Nf6 13.
Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 $14) (9... dxc4 10. Qxc4 Qe7 11. Bg5 $1 {After this strong
move White will get a clear advantage in the center.} (11. e4 e5) 11... h6 12.
Bxf6 Nxf6 13. e4 e5 14. dxe5 Bxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. Qd4 (16. f4 Qa5 17. h3 Be6
18. Qe2 Rad8 19. Kh2 Rxd1 20. Rxd1 Rd8 21. Re1 {1-0 (38) Cheng,B (2504)
-Kargosha,B (2210) Cammeray 2018}) 16... Qh5 {1/2-1/2 (126) Dyachkov,S (2532)
-Dashko,A (2326) Voronezh 2000} 17. e5 $1 Ng4 18. h3 Nxe5 19. g4 Bxg4 20. hxg4
Nxg4 21. Qf4 $16) 10. e4 dxe4 (10... Nxe4 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Ng5 Nf6 13. Nxe4
$14) 11. Ng5 Bb7 12. Ngxe4 Be7 13. Bf4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Nf6 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. c5
$16 {Once again this move tips the balance into White's favor. 1-0 (29)
Mekhitarian,K (2545)-Van Riemsdijk,D (1953) Pocos de Caldas 2018}) (6... Ne4 7.
Qc2 c6 8. O-O f5 9. Ne5 Nd7 10. Nd3 Bd6 11. f3 Nxc3 12. Qxc3 $14 {1-0 (30)
Edouard,R (2635)-Sosa Trani,L (2051) Baku 2016}) (6... b6 $6 7. cxd5 exd5 (7...
Nxd5 8. Bd2 Bb7 9. O-O Nd7 {[%csl Gb4,Gc3,Gd2,Gd5]} 10. e4 Nxc3 11. bxc3) 8.
O-O Bb7 {[%csl Gb7,Gd5]} 9. Ne5 Nbd7 10. Bg5 Be7 11. Rc1 c6 12. Nd3 Rc8 13. Qa4
a5 14. Bh3 $14 {1-0 (50) Anton Guijarro,D (2475)-Nunez Reiz,A (2130) Madrid
2012}) 7. O-O $5 Nc6 (7... c5 8. dxc5 Nc6 9. Qa4 Bd7 10. Ne5 Bxc5 11. Nxd7 Qxd7
(11... Nxd7 12. Qxc4) 12. Rd1 Qc7 13. Qxc4 $14 {with nice pressure for White.})
(7... Bd7 8. Ne5 Bc6 9. e4 $1 Bxc3 10. Nxc6 Nxc6 11. bxc3 e5 12. d5 Ne7 13. Rb1
Nc8 14. f4 $36 {1-0 (40) Leitao,R (2609)-Tsuboi,E (2380) Campinas 2011}) 8. Qa4
Nd5 $1 {Amongst Black's options this is considered the main line. Playing it
Black keeps an extra pawn and forces White to be accurate in order to achieve
something for the sacrificed pawn.} (8... Bd7 {This natural developing move is
met by the tricky} 9. Bg5 a5 (9... Rb8 10. Rad1 Bxc3 11. bxc3 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6
13. Qxc4 Rfc8 {1/2-1/2 (67) Matlakov,M (2735)-Tomashevsky,E (2713) St
Petersburg 2017} 14. e4 $14) ({Accepting White's offered pawn looks suicidal.} 
9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 Nxd4 11. Qxc4 Nc6 (11... Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 $44) 12. Rfd1 {
White's combined pressure has very powerful effect.} Qe7 13. Rab1 Rab8 {
1-0 (41) Roiz,M (2614)-Psakhis,L (2475) Israel 2018} 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Qf4 $14)
10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. a3 ({Another interesting try was played recently by one of
Carlsen's seconds.} 11. Qb5 $5 e5 12. dxe5 Qe6 13. Rfd1 Rfd8 14. Ng5 Qe7 15. e6
fxe6 {1-0 (61) Grandelius,N (2678)-Volokitin,A (2634) Hofheim GER 2018} 16.
Qxb7 Bd6 17. Bxc6 Rab8 18. Qa6 Rb6 19. Qxc4 Rxc6 20. Qg4 $16) 11... Bxc3 (11...
Nb8 12. Qc2 Bxc3 {1/2-1/2 (18) Valenzuela Gomez,F (2384)-Gonzalez Garcia,J 
(2497) Sabadell ESP 2018} 13. Qxc3 Bc6 14. Rfd1 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 c6 16. Qxc4 Nd7
17. b4 $14) (11... Bd6 12. Qxc4 e5 13. d5 Na7 14. Ne4 Qe7 15. Rfc1 Bb5 16. Qc2
Rfd8 {1/2-1/2 (51) Kasimdzhanov,R (2662)-Batchuluun,T (2570) Batumi GEO 2018}
17. Nfg5 g6 18. Nxd6 cxd6 19. h4 $36) 12. bxc3 Qd8 13. Qxc4 {[%csl Ra5,Rb7,Rc7,
Gd4,Ge2] White has a promising position as his opponent weakened his queenside
without getting any compensation for it. Besides, White's central pawns may
play an important role in a later phase of the game.} a4 14. Nd2 (14. Ne5 Na5
15. Qb4 $14) 14... Na5 15. Qb4 Ra7 16. Rab1 b6 17. e3 $14 {1-0 (30) Caruana,F 
(2822)-Karjakin,S (2773) Saint Louis 2018}) (8... Bd6 9. Qxc4 e5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5
11. dxe5 Bxe5 12. Rd1 Qe7 13. Be3 $14 {White's pressure is annoying.}) ({
The slow} 8... a6 {gives White the advantage after} 9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Bxc3
11. bxc3 b5 12. Qc2 Nd5 13. Ba3 Re8 14. Rad1 Qg5 {0-1 (46) Jirka,J (2400)
-Vyskocil,N (2354) Czechia 2003} 15. f4 Qh5 16. Bc1 $16) (8... Rb8 9. Qb5 $1 {
This thematic move is the usual way to regain the sacrificed pawn in some
well-known lines of the Catalan.} Bxc3 10. bxc3 Qd5 {1-0 (46) Rombaldoni,A 
(2479)-De Filomeno,S (2338) Civitanova Marche 2012} 11. a4 $146 a6 12. Qb2 Qh5
13. h3 $14) 9. Qc2 Be7 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gd5b4] With this move Black frees b4 for
the knights.} 10. Rd1 {[#]} {This is the critical position of the main line.
Black plans to keep his extra pawn but to do it he has to decide among varied
choices of similar value. So far none of Black's options had proved to be the
best.} Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black prepares ...b5 and gets the rook out of the
action of the powerful light-squared bishop on g2.} (10... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]
Another way to prepare ...b5.} 11. Ne5 $5 $146 {1-0 (49) Harutyunian,T (2504)
-Babujian,L (2459) Yerevan 2018} Nxe5 12. dxe5 c6 (12... Nb4 13. Qe4 $16) 13.
Ne4 b5 (13... Nb4 14. Qd2 Qxd2 15. Bxd2 Nd5 16. Nd6 Bxd6 17. exd6 f5 18. Rac1
Rd8 (18... b5 19. b3 cxb3 20. axb3 Bd7 21. Ba5 $44) 19. Rxc4 Rxd6 20. Bf4 Rd8
21. Be5 $44) 14. b3 $44) ({The most important game played in this variation is,
without a doubt, the rapid game played between Caruana and So, in the playoff
of the Grand Chess Tour in San Louis Missouri 2018. Caruana scored a fine
victory.} 10... Bd7 $5 11. e4 (11. h4 $5) (11. Bd2 $5) 11... Ncb4 12. Qd2 Nb6 (
12... Nxc3 13. Qxc3 b5 14. Be3 $14) 13. Ne5 Nc6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Qc2 $5 f5 16.
a4 fxe4 {1-0 (62) Caruana,F (2822)-So,W (2780) Saint Louis 2018} 17. a5 $146
Nd5 18. Nxe4 b5 19. axb6 cxb6 20. Qxc4 Qd7 21. Re1 $13) (10... Ncb4 11. Qb1 $5
{In this particular situation I prefer this move, but usually, the queen should
go to d2 in order to recapture with it after Black's ...Nxc3.} (11. Qd2 Nb6)
11... c5 (11... c6 12. Ne5 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nd5 {0-1 (51) Kopylov,A (1779)
-Anchutin, N (2221) Kazan 2018} 14. Bd2 Nb6 15. a4 a5 16. Be4 h6 17. Bxc6 $16) (
11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Nd5 13. Qc2 Bd7 14. Ne5 b5 15. a4 $44) 12. Bd2 cxd4 13.
