[EventType "tourn"]

{In this chapter I will deal with lines where Black plays an early ...Bxc3
followed by ...d6. These lines have a closed nature and are very different
from what we've seen so far and for this precise reason it can be annoying.} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 Bxc3+ (5... d6 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3
Nc6 {Transposes to 5...Bxc3.}) (5... Nc6 6. Nf3 d6 7. Qd3 $5 e5 8. O-O exd4 9.
Nd5 (9. Nxd4 $146 Ne5 10. Qc2 Nxc4 $2 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. Qxc4 $16) 9... Nxd5 (
9... Bc5 10. Bg5) 10. cxd5 Ne5 11. Qxd4 Bc5 12. Qc3 Nxf3+ {1-0 (51) Shepelev,I
(2117)-Palacios Perez,M (2166) Chennai 2012} 13. Qxf3 Re8 14. Bd2 $14) 6. bxc3
d6 ({Another possible set-up is} 6... Nc6 7. Nf3 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6] The fact
that Black is ready to play ...Ba6 forces White to react energetically with} 8.
Ne5 Bb7 9. Bg5 Na5 (9... Nxe5 10. Bxb7 Nxc4 (10... Rb8 11. dxe5) 11. Bxf6 (11.
Bxa8 $1 Qxa8 12. f3) 11... Qxf6 12. Bxa8 Rxa8 13. O-O $14 {0-1 (60) Russell,
C-Ivanov,I (2510) Dearborn 1992}) 10. Bxb7 Nxb7 11. Ng4 $1 {Weakening Black's
kingside gives White an advantage.} d5 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. cxd5 f5 14. Ne3 Nd6
15. Qd3 $16 {1-0 (42) Ribic,K (2315)-Brkic,M (2083) Tuzla 2010}) 7. Nf3 {
Now Black has two main ways to prepare e6-e5.} Nc6 {Tranposes to 5...Bc3.} (
7... c5 8. dxc5 dxc5 {½-½ (30) Onischuk,A (2670)-Papaioannou,I (2625) Bursa
2010} 9. Bf4 $1 Qa5 10. O-O Nc6 (10... Qxc3 11. Qb3 Qa5 12. Ne5 $16) 11. Qb3
$16 {The difficulty to develop his pieces gave White an edge in the game 1-0 
(38) Moiseenko,A (2275)-Kochyev,A (2450) St Petersburg 1995}) (7... Nbd7 {
[%cal Ge6e5] is another less effective way to prepare ...e5.} 8. O-O e5 {[#]}
9. c5 $1 {With this detail White gets rid of the doubled pawns and tries to
open lines for the bishop pair.} exd4 (9... dxc5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1
12. Rxd1 Ng4 13. f4 Rb8 14. h3 Nh6 15. e4 $18 {1-0 (44) Bredemeier,D (2263)
-Erlich,M Germany 2008}) (9... e4 {Black would like to keep the position as
closed as possible.} 10. Nd2 d5 11. c4 c6 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. f3 $1 exf3 14. Nxf3
$14 {White has good chances on both flanks.}) 10. cxd4 dxc5 11. dxc5 c6 {
1-0 (39) Winants,L (2505)-Wians,C (2275) Ostend 1992} (11... Nxc5 12. Ba3) 12.
Qc2 $16) 8. Qd3 $1 {With this odd looking move White will be able to fight for
the center.} ({As we can see this is not the case after the natural looking.} 
8. O-O e5 9. c5 e4 10. Nd2 d5 11. c4 Nxd4 12. cxd5 {0-1 (22) Leontxo,O-Rohde,M
(2440) London 1984} Bg4 $15) 8... e5 9. Nd2 Re8 10. O-O Bg4 (10... Qe7 11. e4
b6 {[%cal Gc8a6,Gc6a5] Black is getting ready to put pressure on the White's
doubled pawns with ...Ba6 and ...Na5. 0-1 (38) Van Laatum,G (2330)-Chuchelov,V
(2490) Belgium 1997} 12. f4 $1 $146 Ba6 13. Nb3 {[%csl Gc1] White frees the
way for his dark-squared bishop while preventing ...Na5.} Na5 ({Trying to
avoid Bg5 is not advisable.} 13... h6 $6 14. Ba3 Qd7 15. fxe5 dxe5 16. Rxf6
gxf6 17. d5 Ne7 18. Rf1 Qa4 19. Bxe7 Rxe7 20. Qd2 Kg7 21. Qf2 $40) (13... exd4
14. e5) (13... exf4 14. e5) 14. Nxa5 bxa5 15. fxe5 dxe5 16. Bg5 Qe6 $1 17. d5 (
17. Bxf6 Bxc4) 17... Qb6+ 18. Kh1 Nd7 19. Qf3 f6 20. Be3 Qd6 21. c5 $1 Nxc5 22.
c4 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5] White's pawns are becoming a real threat as the
blockator seems more vulnerable.}) 11. e4 Qd7 {0-1 (34) Radovanovic,M (2376)
-Drasko,M (2441) Belgrade 2017} 12. Nb3 h6 13. d5 Ne7 14. c5 $16 {[%cal Gc1a3]
White's dark-squred bishop is eager to join the battle from a3.} *

